OS : Windows

ref #18397 should this code not let me see a result for var temp?

```
var a = [34, 203, 3, 746, 200, 984, 198, 764, 9];
 
function bubbleSort(a)
{
    var swapped;
    do {
        swapped = false;
        for (var i=0; i < a.length-1; i++) {
            if (a[i] > a[i+1]) {
                var temp = a[i];
                a[i] = a[i+1];
                a[i+1] = temp;
                swapped = true;
            }
        }
    } while (swapped);
}
 
bubbleSort(a);
console.log(a);
```

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1051190/22319674/bf5956fe-e339-11e6-8ee4-86bf7bb182fa.png)

- VSCode Version: 1.8.1

This behavior exists for a while, that `type`, `let` and `const` is displayed with the wrench icon while `var` and `function` uses different icons.

This issue is specific to `const arrow function`, i.e.:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3254987/22312421/93ad3548-e30c-11e6-8b8c-009a8e57f67c.png)

Since it is `const`, `foo` will always be an arrow function and it should be safe to disregard it as a `const` and consider it as a `function` directly:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3254987/22312459/c89cf446-e30c-11e6-93c5-033baf03d28e.png)

There is a live example:

```ts
export interface AuthenticatePayload {
  authenticating: boolean
  authenticated: boolean,
  username?: string,
  errorMessage?: string
}

export function isAuthenticateAction(action: any)
  : action is FluxStandardAction<AuthenticatePayload, any> {
  return action.type.indexOf(AuthenticateActionType) === 0
}

export const isAuthAction = createActionTypeGuard<AuthenticatePayload>(AuthenticateActionType)

function createActionTypeGuard<Payload>(type: string) {
  return (action: any): action is FluxStandardAction<Payload, void> => {
    return action.type.indexOf(type) === 0
  }
}
```

